\begin_layout Standard
Estrogen binds to the estrogen receptor with 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{D}^{est}=0.1\ nM\ (1\times10^{-10}\ M)$
\end_inset

.
 Testosterone binds with a much lower affinity 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{D}^{tes}=0.1\ mM\ (1\times10^{-4}\ M)$
\end_inset

.
 One difference between estrogen and testosterone in the pocket is hydrogen
 bonding: estrogen has 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 unfulfilled bonds, while testosterone has 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 unfulfilled bond.
 If losing that hydrogen bond costs 
\begin_inset Formula $20\ kJ\cdot mol$
\end_inset

, is this enough to explain the difference in the affinity? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{D}$
\end_inset

 is an equilibrium constant, we can convert it to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{\circ\prime}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G^{\circ\prime}=-RTln(K_{D})$
\end_inset

.
 So:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta G_{estrogen}^{\circ\prime}=-RTln(K_{D}^{est})=-0.0083\times300\times ln(10^{-10})=57.3\ kJ\cdot mol^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset

This is the free energy to dissociate the estrogen from the protein at 
\begin_inset Formula $1\ M$
\end_inset

 estrogen, 
\begin_inset Formula $1M$
\end_inset

 protein, 
\begin_inset Formula $pH\ 7.0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The loss of the hydrogen bond makes binding 
\begin_inset Formula $20\ kJ\cdot mol^{-1}$
\end_inset

 worse.
 This means our predicted dissociation free energy for testosterone is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta G_{tes,predicted}^{\circ\prime}=\Delta G_{estrogen}^{\circ\prime}-20\ kJ\cdot mol^{-1}=57.3-20=37.3\ kJ\cdot mol^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset

(It is 
\begin_inset Formula $20\ kJ\cdot mol^{-1}$
\end_inset

 easier to pull apart testosterone:receptor than estrogen:receptor).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now, convert 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

 back to 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{D}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta G^{\circ\prime}=-RTln(K_{D})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{\Delta G^{\circ\prime}}{RT}=ln(K_{D})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e^{-\frac{\Delta G^{\circ\prime}}{RT}}=K_{D}=e^{-37.3/(0.0083\times300)}=3\times10^{-7}\ M
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{D}$
\end_inset

 is still much lower (better binding) than the observed 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{D}^{tes}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times10^{-4}\ M$
\end_inset

, so some other interaction(s) must be involved in specificity.
 
\end_layout

